# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: curare
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:curare/18-methoxycoronaridine] 18-MC was originally developed by Savant HWP and later acquired by MindMed in 2019 for development as a treatment for opioid use disorder.
[src:curare/18-methoxycoronaridine] A Phase 1 trial in healthy volunteers was completed in 2022 with favorable safety and tolerability.
[src:curare/18-methoxycoronaridine] Due to strategic reprioritization, MindMed discontinued active development of MM-110 in 2023 and has been seeking non-dilutive funding or partners to potentially restart the program; as of 2025 the program remains shelved.
[src:curare/18-methoxycoronaridine] A separate Phase 2 trial in Brazil for cutaneous leishmaniasis (initiated 2017) has unknown status with no published results.
[src:curare/18-methoxycoronaridine] The sites of action in the brain include the medial habenula, interpeduncular nucleus, dorsolateral tegmentum and basolateral amygdala.
[src:curare/18-methoxycoronaridine] (±)-18-MC competitively inhibits α9α10 nAChRs with potencies higher than that at α3β4 and α4β2 nAChRs and directly blocks CaV2.2.
[src:curare/18-methoxycoronaridine] A number of derivatives of 18-MC have been developed, with several of them being superior to 18-MC itself, the methoxyethyl congener ME-18-MC being more potent than 18-MC with similar efficacy, and the methylamino analogue 18-MAC being more effective than 18-MC with around the same potency.
[src:curare/18-methoxycoronaridine] These compounds were also found to act as selective α3β4 nicotinic acetylcholine antagonists, with little or no effect on NMDA receptors.
[src:curare/5-hydroxyindoleacetic-acid] 5-HIAA is tested by 24-hour urine samples combined with an acidic additive to maintain pH below 3.
[src:curare/5-hydroxyindoleacetic-acid] Certain foods like pineapple, kiwi, banana, walnuts and drugs such as acetaminophen, nicotine or caffeine are known to interfere with the measurement.
[src:curare/5-hydroxyindoleacetic-acid] 5-HIAA levels can vary depending on other complications, including tumors, kidney malfunction, and small bowel resection.
[src:curare/5-hydroxyindoleacetic-acid] Since 5-HIAA is a metabolite of serotonin, testing is most frequently performed for the diagnosis of carcinoid tumors of the enterochromaffin (Kultschitzsky) cells of the small intestine, which release large amounts of serotonin.
[src:curare/5-hydroxyindoleacetic-acid] Values greater than 25 mg per 24 hours (higher if the patient has malabsorption) are strong evidence for carcinoid.
[src:curare/5-hydroxyindoleacetic-acid] The normal range is 2 to 6 mg per 24 hours.
[src:curare/5-hydroxyindoleacetic-acid] Low levels of 5-HIAA in the cerebrospinal fluid have been associated with aggressive behavior and suicide by violent means, correlating with diminished serotonin levels.
[src:curare/5-hydroxyindoleacetic-acid] Elevated serotonin (hyperserotonemia) is one of the most common biological findings in autism and 5-HIAA may be elevated in patients with autistic spectrum disorders.
[src:curare/5-hydroxyindoleacetic-acid] 5-HIAA may be normal with nonmetastatic carcinoid tumor and may be normal even with the carcinoid syndrome, particularly in subjects without diarrhea, because some patients with the carcinoid syndrome excrete nonhydroxylated indolic acids.
[src:curare/5-hydroxyindoleacetic-acid] 5-HIAA is increased in untreated patients with malabsorption, who have increased urinary tryptophan metabolites.
[src:curare/5-hydroxyindoleacetic-acid] Such patients include those with celiac disease, tropical sprue, Whipple disease, stasis syndrome, and cystic fibrosis.
[src:curare/5-hydroxyindoleacetic-acid] It is increased in those with chronic intestinal obstruction.
[src:curare/5-hydroxyindoleacetic-acid] Poor correlation exists between 5-HIAA level and the clinical severity of the carcinoid syndrome.
[src:curare/5-hydroxyindoleacetic-acid] 3 recent studies confirm its use as a prognostic factor in this disease.
[src:curare/5-hydroxyindoleacetic-acid] 5-HIAA is the major urinary metabolite of serotonin, a ubiquitous bioactive amine.
[src:curare/5-hydroxyindoleacetic-acid] Serotonin, and consequently 5-HIAA, are produced in excess by most carcinoid tumors, especially those producing the carcinoid syndrome of flushing, hepatomegaly (enlarged liver), diarrhea, bronchospasm, and heart disease.
[src:curare/5-hydroxyindoleacetic-acid] Quantitation of urinary 5-HIAA is the best test for carcinoid, but scrupulous care must be taken that specimen collection and patient preparation have been correct.
[src:curare/5-hydroxyindoleacetic-acid] Carcinoid tumors may cause increased excretion of tryptophan, 5-hydroxytryptophan and histamine as well as serotonin.
[src:curare/5-hydroxyindoleacetic-acid] Serum serotonin assay may detect some carcinoids missed by 5-HIAA assay.
[src:curare/5-hydroxyindoleacetic-acid] The production and metabolism of serotonin, and thus 5-HIAA, is dependent upon the tissue of origin of the tumor.
[src:curare/5-hydroxyindoleacetic-acid] Tumors from midgut cells, such as ileal carcinoid usually contain and release large quantities of serotonin.
[src:curare/5-hydroxyindoleacetic-acid] These amounts may not be fully reflected in the amount of 5-HIAA in urine, because little is metabolized.
[src:curare/5-hydroxyindoleacetic-acid] Foregut tumors lack the decarboxylase enzyme necessary to convert 5-hydroxytryptophan to serotonin, resulting in minimal to no elevation in urinary 5-HIAA levels.
[src:curare/5-hydroxyindoleacetic-acid] Tumors derived from hindgut cells (rectal carcinoid) rarely produce excess serotonin or 5-HIAA.
[src:curare/5-hydroxyindoleacetic-acid] Of 75 patients with carcinoid tumors, 75% had above normal urinary 5-HIAA excretion and 64% had above normal serotonin excretion.
[src:curare/abram-elting-bennett] Bennett published over 50 research articles and several books, including *Fifty Years in Neurology and Psychiatry* (1972), *Alcoholism and the Brain* (1977) and *Huguenots Migration: Descendants' Contributions to America* (1984).
[src:curare/abram-elting-bennett] In the 1930s, Bennett introduced the use of curare to prevent fractures and other adverse side effects caused by shock treatments.
[src:curare/abram-elting-bennett] He also advocated pentylenetetrazol to induce convulsions in patients.
[src:curare/abram-elting-bennett] Bennett was affiliated with Johns Hopkins University, Bishop Clarkson Memorial Hospital in Omaha, Nebraska and the California Pacific Medical Center.
[src:curare/abram-elting-bennett] He contributed to the second edition of the *Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders* and earlier was also one of the many consultants involved in the creation of the DSM-1.
[src:curare/abuta] The genus consists of dioecious climbers or rarely erect trees or shrubs (*Abuta grandifolia*) with simple leaves.
[src:curare/abuta] Male flowers have six sepals, in two whorls, no petals , six stamens (which are connate or free, and introrse), and anthers with a longitudinal or transverse dehiscence.
[src:curare/abuta] Female flowers have sepals and petals as in the male, six staminodes, three carpels, ovoid drupes, a woody endocarp, a septiform condyle, a ruminate endosperm, a curved embryo, and appressed cotyledons.
[src:curare/abuta] The genera *Anelasma* Miers and *Batschia* Thunb. have been brought into synonymy with *Abuta*.
[src:curare/aqw051] It was later licensed it to Vanda Pharmaceuticals and who are evaluating it in phase 3 clinical trials for phobic disorders and social anxiety.
[src:curare/atc-code-m03] Codes for veterinary use (ATCvet codes) can be created by placing the letter Q in front of the human ATC code: for example, **QM03**.
[src:curare/atc-code-m03] ATCvet codes without corresponding human ATC codes are cited with the leading Q in the following list.
[src:curare/atc-code-m03] National versions of the ATC classification may include additional codes not present in this list, which follows the WHO version.
[src:curare/curare] Curare is prepared by boiling the bark of one of the dozens of plant sources, leaving a dark, heavy paste that can be applied to arrow or dart heads.
[src:curare/curare] These poisons cause weakness of the skeletal muscles and, when administered in a sufficient dose, eventual death by asphyxiation due to paralysis of the diaphragm.
[src:curare/curare] In medicine, curare has been used as a treatment for tetanus and strychnine poisoning and as a paralyzing agent for surgical procedures.
[src:curare/curare] The word 'curare' is derived from *wurari*, from the Carib language of the Macusi of Guyana.
[src:curare/curare] It has its origins in the Carib phrase "mawa cure" meaning of the Mawa vine, scientifically known as *Strychnos toxifera*.
[src:curare/curare] Curare is also known among indigenous peoples as ampi, woorari, woorara, woorali, wourali, wouralia, ourare, ourari, urare, urari, and uirary.
[src:curare/curare] The region throughout which curare has been used is a wide zone covering parts of the Amazon .
[src:curare/curare] The noun 'curare' is not to be confused with the Latin verb 'curare' ('to heal, cure, take care of').
[src:curare/curare] In 1895, pharmacologist Rudolf Boehm sought to classify the various alkaloid poisons based on the containers used for their preparation.
[src:curare/curare] He believed curare could be categorized into three main types as seen below.
[src:curare/curare] However useful it appeared, it became rapidly outmoded.
[src:curare/curare] Richard Gill, a plant collector, found that the indigenous peoples began to use a variety of containers for their curare preparations, henceforth invalidating Boehm's basis of classification.
[src:curare/curare] Curare was used as a paralyzing poison by many South American indigenous people.
[src:curare/curare] Since it was too expensive to be used in warfare, curare was mainly used for hunting.
[src:curare/curare] The prey was shot by arrows or blowgun darts dipped in curare, leading to asphyxiation owing to the inability of the victim's respiratory muscles to contract.
[src:curare/curare] In particular, the poison was used by the Kalinago, indigenous people of the Lesser Antilles in the Caribbean, on the tips of their arrows.
[src:curare/curare] In addition, the Yagua people, indigenous to Colombia and northeastern Peru, commonly used these toxins via blowpipes to target prey 30 to 40 paces distant.
[src:curare/curare] Due to its popularity among the indigenous people as means of paralyzing prey, certain tribes would create monopolies from curare production.
[src:curare/curare] Thus, curare became a symbol of wealth among the indigenous populations.
[src:curare/curare] In 1596, Sir Walter Raleigh mentioned the arrow poison in his book *Discovery of the Large, Rich, and Beautiful Empire of Guiana* (which relates to his travels in Trinidad and Guayana), though the poison he described was possibly not curare.
[src:curare/curare] In 1780, Abbe Felix Fontana discovered that it acted on the voluntary muscles rather than the nerves and the heart.
[src:curare/curare] In 1832, Alexander von Humboldt gave the first western account of how the toxin was prepared from plants by Orinoco River natives.
[src:curare/curare] During 1811–1812, Sir Benjamin Collins Brody experimented with curare (*woorara*).
[src:curare/curare] He was the first to show that curare does not kill the animal and the recovery is complete if the animal's respiration is maintained artificially.
[src:curare/curare] In 1825, Charles Waterton described a classical experiment in which he kept a curarized female donkey alive by artificial respiration with a bellows through a tracheostomy.
[src:curare/curare] Waterton is also credited with bringing curare to Europe.
[src:curare/curare] Robert Hermann Schomburgk, who was a trained botanist, identified the vine as one of the genus *Strychnos* and gave it the now accepted name *Strychnos toxifera*.
[src:curare/curare] George Harley (1829–1896) showed in 1850 that curare (*wourali*) was effective for the treatment of tetanus and strychnine poisoning.
[src:curare/curare] From 1887, the Burroughs Wellcome catalogue listed under its 'Tabloids' brand name, 1⁄12 grain (5.4 mg) tablets of curare (price: 8 shillings) for use in preparing a solution for hypodermic injection.
[src:curare/curare] In 1914, Henry Hallett Dale (1875–1968) described the physiological actions of acetylcholine.
[src:curare/curare] After 25 years, he showed that acetylcholine is responsible for neuromuscular transmission, which can be blocked by curare.
[src:curare/curare] The best known and historically most important toxin (because of its medical applications) is d-tubocurarine.
[src:curare/curare] It was isolated from the crude drug – from a museum sample of curare – in 1935 by Harold King of London, working in Sir Henry Dale's laboratory.
[src:curare/curare] King also established its chemical structure.
[src:curare/curare] Pascual Scannone, a Venezuelan anesthesiologist who trained and specialized in New York City, did extensive research on curare as a possible paralyzing agent for patients during surgical procedures.
[src:curare/curare] In 1942, he became the first person in Latin America to use curare during a medical procedure when he successfully performed a tracheal intubation in a patient to whom he administered curare for muscle paralysis at the El Algodonal Hospital in Caracas, Venezuela.
[src:curare/curare] After its introduction in 1942, curare/curare-derivatives became a widely used paralyzing agent during medical and surgical procedures.
[src:curare/curare] Later, it has been superseded by a number of synthetic curare-like agents, such as pancuronium, which have a similar pharmacodynamic profile, but fewer side effects.
[src:curare/curare] The various components of curare are organic compounds classified as either isoquinoline or indole alkaloids.
[src:curare/curare] Tubocurarine is one of the major active components in the South American dart poison.
[src:curare/curare] As an alkaloid, tubocurarine is a naturally occurring compound that consists of nitrogenous bases, although the chemical structure of alkaloids is highly variable.
[src:curare/curare] Tubocurarine and C toxiferine consist of a cyclic system with quaternary ammonium ions.
[src:curare/curare] On the other hand, while acetylcholine does not contain a cyclic system, it does contain a quaternary ammonium ion.
[src:curare/curare] Because of this shared moiety, curare alkaloids can bind readily to the active site of receptors for acetylcholine (ACh) at the neuromuscular junction, blocking nerve impulses from being sent to the skeletal muscles, effectively paralyzing the muscles of the body.
[src:curare/curare] Curare is an example of a non-depolarizing muscle relaxant that blocks the nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR), one of the two types of acetylcholine (ACh) receptors, at the neuromuscular junction.
[src:curare/curare] The main toxin of curare, d-tubocurarine, occupies the same position on the receptor as ACh with an equal or greater affinity, and elicits no response, making it a competitive antagonist.
[src:curare/curare] The antidote for curare poisoning is an acetylcholinesterase (AChE) inhibitor (anti-cholinesterase), such as physostigmine or neostigmine.
[src:curare/curare] By blocking ACh degradation, AChE inhibitors raise the amount of ACh in the neuromuscular junction; the accumulated ACh will then correct for the effect of the curare by activating the receptors not blocked by toxin at a higher rate.
[src:curare/curare] The time of onset varies from within one minute (for tubocurarine in intravenous administration, penetrating a larger vein), to between 15 and 25 minutes (for intramuscular administration, where the substance is applied in muscle tissue).
[src:curare/curare] It is harmless if taken orally because curare compounds are too large and highly charged to pass through the lining of the digestive tract to be absorbed into the blood.
[src:curare/curare] For this reason, people can safely eat curare-poisoned prey, and it has no effect on its flavor.
[src:curare/curare] Isolated attempts to use curare during anesthesia date back to 1912 by Arthur Lawen of Leipzig, but curare came to anesthesia via psychiatry (electroplexy).
[src:curare/curare] In 1939 Abram Elting Bennett used it to modify metrazol induced convulsive therapy.
[src:curare/curare] Muscle relaxants are used in modern anesthesia for many reasons, such as providing optimal operating conditions and facilitating intubation of the trachea.
[src:curare/curare] Before muscle relaxants, anesthesiologists needed to use larger doses of the anesthetic agent, such as ether, chloroform or cyclopropane to achieve these aims.
[src:curare/curare] Such deep anesthesia risked killing patients who were elderly or had heart conditions.
[src:curare/curare] The source of curare in the Amazon was first researched by Richard Evans Schultes in 1941.
[src:curare/curare] Since the 1930s, it was being used in hospitals as a muscle relaxant.
[src:curare/curare] He discovered that different types of curare called for as many as 15 ingredients, and in time helped to identify more than 70 species that produced the drug.
[src:curare/curare] In the 1940s, it was used on a few occasions during surgery as it was mistakenly thought to be an analgesic or anesthetic.
[src:curare/curare] The patients reported feeling the full intensity of the pain though they were not able to do anything about it since they were essentially paralyzed.
[src:curare/curare] On January 23, 1942, Harold Griffith and Enid Johnson gave a synthetic preparation of curare (Intercostrin/Intocostrin) to a patient undergoing an appendectomy (to supplement conventional anesthesia).
[src:curare/curare] Safer curare derivatives, such as rocuronium and pancuronium, have superseded d-tubocurarine for anesthesia during surgery.
[src:curare/curare] When used with halothane d-tubocurarine can cause a profound fall in blood pressure in some patients as both the drugs are ganglion blockers.
[src:curare/curare] However, it is safer to use d-tubocurarine with ether.
[src:curare/curare] In 1954, an article was published by Beecher and Todd suggesting that the use of muscle relaxants (drugs similar to curare) increased death due to anesthesia nearly sixfold.
[src:curare/curare] Modern anesthetists have at their disposal a variety of muscle relaxants for use in anesthesia.
[src:curare/curare] The ability to produce muscle relaxation irrespective of sedation has permitted anesthetists to adjust the two effects independently and on the fly to ensure that their patients are safely unconscious and sufficiently relaxed to permit surgery.
[src:curare/curare] The use of neuromuscular blocking drugs carries with it the risk of anesthesia awareness.
[src:curare/curare] There are dozens of plants from which isoquinoline and indole alkaloids with curarizing effects can be isolated, and which were utilized by indigenous tribes of Central and South America for the production of arrow poisons.
[src:curare/curare] Some plants in the family Aristolochiaceae have also been reported as sources.
[src:curare/curare] Alkaloids with curare-like activity are present in plants of the fabaceous genus *Erythrina*.
[src:curare/curare] Administration must be parenteral, as gastro-intestinal absorption is ineffective.
[src:curare/curare] The toxicity of curare alkaloids in humans has not been systematically established, but it is considered highly toxic and slow-acting, with a lowest reported lethal dose of 375 μg/kg (unknown route of administration).
[src:curare/curare] Death can be prevented by artificial ventilation until curare subsides and muscle function is regained, in which case no permanent effects of poisoning occur.
[src:curare/curare] In 1807, Alexander von Humboldt provided the first eye-witness account of curare preparation.
[src:curare/curare] A mixture of young bark scrapings of the *Strychnos* plant, other cleaned plant parts, and occasionally snake venom is boiled in water for two days.
[src:curare/curare] This liquid is then strained and evaporated to create a dark, heavy, viscid paste that would be tested for its potency later.
[src:curare/curare] This curare paste was described to be very bitter in taste.
[src:curare/curare] In 1938, Richard Gill and his expedition collected samples of processed curare and described its method of traditional preparation; one of the plant species used at that time was *Chondrodendron tomentosum*.
[src:curare/curare] Various irritating herbs, stinging insects, poisonous worms, and various parts of amphibians and reptiles are added to the preparation.
[src:curare/curare] Some of these accelerate the onset of action or increase the toxicity; others prevent the wound from healing or blood from coagulating.
[src:curare/curare] Curare poisoning can be indicated by typical signs of neuromuscular-blocking drugs such as paralysis including respiration but not directly affecting the heart.
[src:curare/curare] Curare poisoning can be managed by artificial respiration such as mouth-to-mouth resuscitation.
[src:curare/curare] In a study of 29 army volunteers that were paralyzed with curare, artificial respiration managed to keep oxygen saturation always above 85%, a level at which there is no evidence of altered state of consciousness.
[src:curare/curare] Yet, curare poisoning mimics total locked-in syndrome in that there is paralysis of every voluntarily controlled muscle in the body (including the eyes), making it practically impossible for the victim to confirm consciousness while paralyzed.
[src:curare/curare] Spontaneous breathing is resumed after the end of the duration of action of curare, which is generally between 30 minutes and 8 hours, depending on the variant of the toxin and dosage.
[src:curare/curare] Cardiac muscle is not directly affected by curare, but if more than four to six minutes has passed since respiratory cessation the cardiac muscle may stop functioning due to oxygen deprivation, making cardiopulmonary resuscitation including chest compressions necessary.
[src:curare/curare] Since tubocurarine and the other components of curare bind reversibly to the ACh receptors, treatment for curare poisoning involves adding an acetylcholinesterase (AChE) inhibitor, which will stop the destruction of acetylcholine so that it can compete with curare.
[src:curare/curare] This can be done by administration of acetylcholinesterase (AChE) inhibitors such as pyridostigmine, neostigmine, physostigmine, and edrophonium.
[src:curare/curare] Acetylcholinesterase is an enzyme used to break down the acetylcholine (ACh) neurotransmitter left over in motor neuron synapses.
[src:curare/curare] The aforementioned inhibitors, termed "anticurare" drugs, reversibly bind to the enzyme's active site, prohibiting its ability to bind to its original target, ACh.
[src:curare/curare] By blocking ACh degradation, AChE inhibitors can effectively raise the amount of ACh present in the neuromuscular junction.
[src:curare/curare] The accumulated ACh will then correct for the effect of the curare by activating the receptors not blocked by toxin at a higher rate, restoring activity to the motor neurons and bodily movement.
